# TextSpeeder Wiki

## Screen 1 — Upload / Import Screen

### Overview

The **Upload / Import Screen** is the first working screen of TextSpeeder. Its purpose is simple: **allow users to bring text into the application quickly and easily**.

Users may want to read content from many different sources such as documents, articles, notes, or books. This screen acts as a **universal gateway for importing text** into the app.

The goal is to remove friction. A user should be able to open the app, add text from almost any source, and move forward in seconds.

This screen **does not edit, clean, or prepare the text**. It only collects it.

---

# Purpose of the Upload Screen

The Upload Screen is responsible for:

• accepting text from different sources
• converting the content into plain text
• confirming that the text was successfully imported

Once the text is imported, the user moves to the next screen where editing and cleaning can happen.

---

# Supported Ways to Add Text

TextSpeeder should allow users to import text in multiple ways so that they can work with content from any source.

---

## Upload Documents

Users can upload documents from their device. This allows them to read content from files they already have.

Common supported document types include:

* PDF files
* Word documents
* Plain text files

This feature is useful for reading:

* research papers
* reports
* essays
* study materials
* ebooks or document chapters

Users simply choose a file and the app extracts the readable text.

---

## Drag and Drop Files

To make uploading even faster, users can drag a file directly into the app.

Instead of browsing folders, they simply drag a document onto the upload area and drop it.

This makes the experience quick and intuitive, especially for desktop users.

---

## Paste Text

Users can paste text directly from their clipboard.

This is useful when copying text from:

* websites
* emails
* online articles
* digital notes
* documents

The user simply pastes the content and the text appears inside the app.

---

## Type Text Manually

Some users may want to type text directly into the application.

A large text area allows users to write or paste their own content.

This can be useful for:

* practicing reading
* writing short notes
* entering custom text

---

# Import from Web Articles

Users can import text from a web page by pasting the article link.

The system extracts the main content from the page and removes elements that are not part of the article.

For example, the system ignores:

* advertisements
* navigation menus
* sidebars
* comments

This allows users to quickly convert a web article into a clean reading text.

---

# Import from Images (OCR)

Sometimes text exists inside images, such as:

* photos of book pages
* screenshots of articles
* scanned documents

The Upload Screen can extract text from these images.

This allows users to turn photographed text into readable digital text inside the app.

This feature is particularly helpful for students or readers who work with printed material.

---

# Import from YouTube Transcripts

Users may also want to read the transcript of a video.

By pasting a YouTube link, the system can retrieve the video’s subtitles and convert them into text.

This makes it possible to read:

* lectures
* speeches
* interviews
* educational videos

instead of watching them.

---

# Import from Ebook Files

Some users read books in digital formats.

The app can support importing ebook files so that users can load book chapters into the reading system.

This allows readers to apply speed-reading techniques to ebooks.

---

# Demo Text Library

For first-time users, the app should provide example texts.

These demo texts allow users to try the reading system without needing to upload their own content.

Examples might include:

* famous speeches
* short stories
* educational passages

This helps users immediately experience the app.

---

# Import Summary

After text is imported, the app should briefly summarize the content.

This might include information such as:

* number of words
* length of the text
* estimated reading time

This helps users understand the size of the material they are about to read.

---

# Clear or Reset

Users should always be able to reset the screen.

If they imported the wrong file or pasted incorrect text, they can clear the content and start again.

This keeps the experience simple and forgiving.

---

# Continue to the Next Step

Once the user is satisfied with the imported text, they can proceed to the next screen.

The next screen allows them to **edit and clean the text before reading**.

---

# Design Philosophy

The Upload Screen is designed with one principle in mind:

**Bring text into the system as quickly as possible.**

All editing, formatting, and reading configuration happen later in the workflow.

By keeping this screen focused on **text acquisition**, the app remains simple, fast, and easy to use.

---

# Summary

The Upload / Import Screen is the **entry point for all reading content** in TextSpeeder.

It allows users to import text from:

* documents
* websites
* images
* videos
* manual input

By supporting many input methods, the application becomes flexible enough to handle content from almost any source.

Once the text is imported, the user moves forward to the next stage where the content can be cleaned and prepared for reading.
